syntax.html.body:
Locale and KeyPath SyntaxYou can use the bellow structure locale:{
  key1: 'this is message1', // basic
  nested: { // nested
    message1: 'this is nested message1'
  },
  errors: [ // array
    'this is 0 error code message',
    { // array in object
       inernal1: 'this is internal 1 error message'
    },
    [ // array in array
       'this is nested array error 1'
    ]
  ]
}
In the above locale structure,  You can translate with using below key paths.

  {{ $t('key1') }}

  {{ $t('nested.message1') }}

  {{ $t('errors[0]') }}

  {{ $t('errors[1].internal1') }}

  {{ $t('errors[2][0]') }}

Ouput the following:

  this is message1

  this is nested message1

  this is 0 error code message

  this is internal 1 error message

  this is nested array error 1

linked.html.body:
Linked translationIf there's a translation key that will always have the same concrete text as another one you can just link to it. To link to another translation key, all you have to do is to prefix its contents with an @: sign followed by the full name of the translation key including the namespace you want to link to.Locale the following:var locales = {
  en: {
    message: {
      the_world: 'the world',
      dio: 'DIO:',
      linked: '@:message.dio @:message.the_world !!!!'
    }
  }
}
Template the following:{{ $t('message.linked') }}
Output the following:DIO: the world !!!!

